funding_code: COMBINATION CF DIRECT LOAN/GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchaseacustom Toyne fire apparatus pumper with a 1200 gallon tank and a 1250 gallon per minute pump. It is a 5-person cab with air-pack seats for 4, which allows firefighters to have their gear on and be ready to work once they get to the scene. This new truck is a diesel, automatic transmission with twice the equipment storage capacity as the current truck. It is Foam-ready, which will expand the types of fires the department can handle. The citys current pumper truck is 27 years old. Yearly maintenance costs for the truck motor and firefighting pump are increasing every year. The cab is not designed for firefighters in gear to ride to a call, which causes a slower response once on scene, as they must put on their gear. The current truck lacks safety restraints for some riders. As the commercial and industrial areas of Humboldt grow, there is a need for increased water flow and reliability of the fire apparatus.This project will provide rural residents with access to new and improved public safety.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment is to purchase abrush fire truck for the fire department. Logan Township is part of the Humboldt Volunteer Fire Department providing fire protection to the southwest part of Allen County, Kansas. The new truck will replace an existing 1977 model, which does not meet all of the National Fire Protection Association safety standards for this type of apparatus. The maintenance on this vehicle has become increasingly costly over the past several years. With the purchase of this new truck, fire fighters and residents of the area will have new and improved public safety services.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used topurchase and install aheating and air conditioning system for the city hall, library and community center. The current system is old, unreliable and has many service calls for repairs. At times, those repairs have caused the cancellation of activities.This building is used for multiple purposes: It isthe city hall where the city offices are operated and residents can conduct business. Its the public library, and its a community center for gatherings with family and residents for a wide variety of events. Its a fitness center that is opened for use 24 hours a day 7 days a week for the community and county. The gymnasium is used in bad or cold weather by an active group of pickle-ball players. There is a health and wellness coordinator that schedules fitness center activities for the community both inside and outside of the center. Its an emergency shelter for the general public to go when there is a natural disaster in the area. With so many people relying on this building, it is essential that it have a new and reliable heating and air conditioning system in place for the benefit of the community and surrounding area.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate and improve the city hall/community center. Redfield Community Center was built in 1960 and currently houses the City Hall office. It also serves as a community voting center and hosts various community events and private gatherings. The buildings age, along with deferred maintenance, has resulted in a need for significant upgrades. Upgrades will be made to the restroom to make it accessible to people with disabilities. Installation of a water heater, heating and cooling system, new doors and windows will improve energy efficiency and lower operational costs. Once the project is complete, it will provide rural residents with new and improved public facilities.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used tocomplete street improvements, curb, guttering and storm water grading within the city of Cottonwood Falls. Many city streets have been overlaid multiple times, patched and treated with various maintenance measures throughout their service life. Streets have warped cross sections, reduced storm water capacity in the gutter, and irregular profiles resulting in potholes and ponding. This project will address the most immediate street needs through patching, replacement and storm sewer installation. The project includes approximately 13,850 square yards of asphalt milling, 2,710 tons of hot mix asphalt surface replacement, 3,510 square yards of concrete pavement, 31,200 square yards of chip and seal, 3,350 feet of sidewalk, and storm water grading and improvements. Once this project is completed, the city will have new safe and improved streets for residents and visitors for years to come.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate Ashland High Schoolto provide equal access to restroom facilities for individuals with disabilities and to bring the building into ADA compliance. The current high school was built in 1962. No renovations or additions have been made to the building to provide accessible restrooms for individuals with disabilities. The school is currently using one faculty restroom, as its designated handicap accessible restroom. This restroom provides only limited access and was not intentionally designed to be ADA compliant.The project will renovate two restrooms, one for men and the other for women. This will create a set of restrooms that will be ADA compliant. The restrooms will be located at the main entrance of the high school. When the project is complete, individuals with disabilities will have better access in the high school to ADA compliant restrooms.

program: SEARCH - Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant (WEP)
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) SEARCH GRANTS WASTE ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment is to be used to complete a Preliminary Engineering Report surrounding the Citys wastewater system. The issues that have occurred with the system are at the lift station and are mainly caused by storm water inflow infiltration into the sewer mains. During these rain storm events, the backup pump becomes engaged, heats up and has been damaged. Infiltration is happening through cracks and holes in the sewer pipes, residential sump pumps, and damage from meat locker, grease and animal parts in system. This Preliminary Engineering Report will give the City information it needs to make informed decisions on what to do to get the wastewater system operating more efficiently and meet permit limits. This will benefit the community by having are safe and reliable sewer system.

program: SEARCH - Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant (WEP)
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) SEARCH GRANTS WASTE ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be to complete a Preliminary Engineering Report on the wastewater system for the city of Miltonvale. This evaluation of their wastewater collection system and treatment facility is needed to determine the improvements necessary to get the wastewater facility to operate more efficiently and meet permit limits. Over the past couple years, their system has been experiencing excessive erosion on the lagoon cells dikes, which has allowed unauthorized discharges. The city needs to know what issues need to be addressed and select a path to follow, so that the wastewater system will function properly for years to come.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used replace and improve Dickinson County Rural Water District No. 1s water systems. The project that is currently in construction is to replace roughly 400,000 feet of water line, 74 gate valves, 18 flush hydrants and chlorination equipment. The district will upgrade the three storage tanks with new interior and exterior painting. Rural Development has already awarded funds in the amount of $2,319,000.00 in a direct loan and $1,305,000.00 in grant funds to initially complete the project. Due to changes during construction, these additional funds are needed to see the project to completion. When the project is complete, the district will have new and improved facilities to provide safe and dependable water for years to come.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) ECWAG - APPROPRIATED $1,000,000 LIMIT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to complete improvements to the citys water supply system.The city has experienced severely reduced water levels in their two wells over the last seven years; dropping approximately 10-15 feet lower than normal. On September 2, 2021, the Kansas Governor issued a Declaration of Drought Emergency for the area. The proposed improvement project will include the installation of a new water supply well, well house, well metering, electrical telemetry, and more to provide a long-term solution to the citys ongoing water supply issues. Once this project is completed the city will have a safe and reliable source of water for many years to come.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: ASSISTED LIVING FACILITIES FOR THE ELDERLY
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment is to be used to cover the increased cost of construction materials on a senior living campus consisting of 14 units ofskilled nursing and 12 apartments for assisted living. The skilled nursing would have 14-units built on the Greenhouse concept of universal care. This includes communal dining, an open kitchen and a home-like feeling among the residents and staff. The staff will provide meal preparation, as well as nursing services.The assisted living portion will consist of 12 apartments (10-1 bedroom and 2-2 bedroom units). Each apartment will have a living room and small kitchenette. These apartments are arranged around a community dining and living space. There is an open kitchen, community room, a spa and beauty shop. A meal program of three meals per day will be provided to the assisted living residents along with social, health and recreational programs. A community wellness area will be a part of the facility. Once the project is completed, it will provide the community with quality senior health care and housing that will allow them to stay closer tofamily living in the surrounding area.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to rehabilitate the wastewater collection system and lift station. The project includes the repair and/or replacement of 1,307 linear feet of pipe, and the installation of approximately 4,760 linear feet of pipe and lift station pumps. The current wastewater collection system is in poor condition and experiencing a large number of line breaks. Several components of the system require an abnormal amount of maintenance. Previous investments made on this project were a $11,500 Rural Development grant and $25,000 from the city that were used to complete the Preliminary Engineering Report on the project. After the improvements are completed, the city will have a safe and reliable wastewater collection system for many years to come.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) PRE-DEVELOPMENT GRANTS - WASTE ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to hire an engineering firm to perform a detailed evaluation of the citys wastewater utility system and treatment facility. The evaluation will determine the improvements needed for the wastewater facility to operate more efficiently and meet permitted limits. The engineering firm will complete the Preliminary Engineering Report, Geotechnical Study and Floodplain Analysis on the citys current system. Over the past few years the ammonia level from the system has been higher than the permitted amount set by the Kansas Department of Health and Environment. Once this evaluation is completed, the city will have the information they need to develop a financially feasible final project that will correct the deficiencies in the system.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and installaboiler system for the county courthouse. The courthousewas built in 1929 and is on both the Kansas Historic Register and the National Historic Register. The existing system has reached the end of its useful life and needs continual repairs, of which parts are difficult to find due to the age of the system. Additionally, the existing system is no longer energy efficient. The new system will come with a one-year warranty and the county has entered into a contract for continued maintenance, eliminating emergency costs of labor and parts, which had proven to be high costs in the past. When the project is completed, the county will have an energy efficient system that will provide heat toemployees and citizens who work and enter the building for business for many years to come.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will provide water improvements for the town of Nortonville, Kansas. The city has two active groundwater wells, over 60 years old, and one recently abandoned well. One fourth (1.5 miles) of the waterline is 80-year-old cast iron pipe, which is corroding and failing. The water has a noticeable discoloration due to a combination of corroded pipeline and an inferior water supply. The groundwater is high in hardness, iron, and manganese. This project represents the second phase of the rehabilitation of the existing water system where two-thirds of the distribution system was previously replaced. The proposed project will replace the abandoned well and replace the remaining 1.5 mile portion of cast iron waterline with 9,300 feet of 4-inch PVC pipe, construct two new wells with chemical feed buildings, and includes 185 new meters, 90 meter settings, 14 valves, and 9 fire hydrants. The water quality will be improved by eliminating the cast iron corroded pipeline and having improved wells.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to repair the Citys existing water distribution system. The current system consists of an underground storage tank, a stand pipe and cast-iron water mains believed to be 100 years old or more. Due to the systems age and the problems, repairs are becoming difficult and costly. The proposed project is the first of a multi-phased plan to improve the Citys water system. This phase will replace about 30 percent of the Citys water lines. This includes associated valves, hydrants and surface restoration. These improvements to the water system will provide reliable and safe water to the residents of the community.

program: SEARCH - Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant (WEP)
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) SEARCH GRANTS WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to complete a preliminary engineering report for the Citys water system. This report will evaluate the water distribution system and wells. It will determine the necessary improvements needed to get the water facility to operate more economically, reduce repairs, and have a water supply that will meet Kansas Department of Health and Environment permit requirements. Over the past couple years the City has experienced numerous line breaks in the water distribution system. This has lead to higher operating and maintenance costs on the water facility. Once this report is completed, it will assist the City in developing a financially feasible final water project.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will provide improvements to the Mullinvilles water distribution system. The current system has gaps in the roof of the water storage tank and other issues due to its age. The existing water tower is over 70 years old. The proposed project will consist of removal of dead-ends, installation of 13,900 linear feet of six-inch water line, 900 linear feet of eight-inch line, 64 valves, 98 water service connections and 17 fire hydrants. This will improve the water pressure in the entire water distribution system and increase reliability of the water system. Once complete, the City will have an improved, safe and dependable water distribution system to provide water to their residents.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will rehabilitate the sewer system to Chetopa, Kansas. A partial repair was completed in 2010, but portions of the system were not improved. Those areas now have a high level of deterioration. Water is entering during rain events through cracks and breaks in the collection mains and at manholes causing sewage back up in residential properties and manholes, allowing untreated waste on the ground. These defective areas are causing multiple sanitary sewer overflows to occur in the system. The repairs will complete the rehabilitation of the system and include approximately 888 vertical feet of manhole repair, 275 service tap repairs, 50 point repairs, and 34,000 feet of fold and form liner or cast-in-place pipe. The rehabilitated system will correct a health and sanitary issue for residents in Chetopa.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct and expand the citys water system. The existing water treatment plant is in poor condition and does not adequately treat the citys potable water.The city entered into an agreement in April 2019 to purchase potable water from the city of LaCygne, contingent upon the completion of this project. This project consists of 20,700 feet force main to be installed between the two cities, 147,730 feet of pipe for the distribution system, 244 hydrants and the construction of a 250,000 gallon elevated water storage tank. Upon completion of this project the city will be capable of providing metered potable water.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct water services to new customers of Linn County Rural Water District No. 2. Currently the water district doesnt have the existing capacity to provide water to upwards of 100 potential new customers. The project includes the installation ofnearly five miles of water line. It will also include 40 service meters, 24 galvanized valves and a new 50,000 gallon elevated storage tank that will provide benefits beyond the addition of the new users. Once the project is completed the rural water district will be able to provide safe and reliable water to new users on their system.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for construction of a new water well, standpipe and distribution system for the City of Vermillion. The current water system has high levels of iron and manganese. The cast iron pipe infrastructure was installed in 1936 and most of the valves are underneath several inches of asphalt and cannot be located. The citys current water tower has lead based paint on the exterior and needs to be repainted. The water system has trouble maintaining chlorine residuals so hydrants are flushed weekly and several of the fire hydrants leak badly when they are in use. Most residents do not drink the water due to the taste and odor. This project will be the first phase of the rehabilitation of the existing water system, which is to include construction of new supply wells, a new stand pipe for water storage, installing approximately 2,500 linear feet of force main, 1,600 linear feet of pipe to connect new storage tank to existing distribution system, and dismantle the existing elevated storage tank. Previously, Rural Development awarded a $30,000.00 Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households grant to the city which assisted in locating the new water source.Once this project is completed, the city will provide residents with safe and clean water for their daily use.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate a facility for the citys public library. The existing library is housed in a building that was constructed in 1929 with three separate store fronts. In 1993 the building was combined to a 2,800 square foot library space. The citys Public Building Commission purchased a 4,500 square foot facility that was built in 1979, and would need interior renovations before becoming the citys new public library. The new facility will be Americans with Disabilities Act compliant and include purchases of accessible shelving, tables, chairs and other furnishings. The new facility will have interactive childrens and technology areas. The facility will have comfortable seating, study spaces, community room, and an outdoor classroom. This new public library will provide residents with a library that will grow and adapt with them, along with providing access to new and improved cultural and educational services.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase avehicle and equipment for the Fire-Rescue Departments Code Enforcement within the city. Currently the department is using other emergency service vehicles to perform code inspections and other related enforcement duties. When this vehicle is being used for these purposes, the department has a vehicle placed out of service, which causes delays in response times for when an emergency occurs. This will help with response times and delays for having a vehicle out of service. Once the new vehicle is in use, the residents will have new and improved public safety.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace a section of waterlines for the City of Caney. This project received previous funding from Rural Development in the amounts of a $2,741,000.00 loan and two grants for $265,000.00 and $600,000 on Aug. 29, 2018, and another $693,000.00 loan on May 19, 2020. This additional funding is needed to cover costs associated with replacement of the additional water lines found during the excavation and repairing of existing waterlines. Once the project is completed the community will have a safe and reliable water system for years to come.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Arts, Entertainment, and Recreation (71)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate the interior of the Art and History Center located in Council Grove, Kan. The renovations will include the installation of heating and air conditioning, two ADA accessible restrooms and other facilities, flooring, custom stage, chair lift, and shelving for displays. Currently this building has no heating and cooling systems and is not ADA accessible. This building will be used for multi-purposes, such as: cultural, historic and artistic educational presentations, events, exhibits, films, displays, and other activities showcasing the Heart of the Flints area. The center is essential to preserving the history of the community, especially the Santa Fe Trail. The center will provide and improved access to the community and tourists to come and see the history of the area.

funding_code: RURAL BUSINESS-COOPERATIVE SERVICE - RURAL INNOVATION STRONGER ECONOMY GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will support a jobs accelerator partnership to improve the ability of rural communities to create high wage jobs, accelerate the formation of new businesses, and help rural communities identify and maximize local assets. Neosho County Community College, an institution of higher learning, is partnering with Southeast Kansas Works, a local workforce development board, and the Chanute Regional Development Authority, an economic development organization, to renovate 24,000 square feet of the Neosho County Innovation & Technology Center (NCITC) to provide advanced manufacturing training, business development support, and programming for entrepreneurs and members of the community in nine rural counties. The program will provide training to 50 students and support 75 community partners within the first year of operations.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used torebuild and repair two existing boiler units and address a safety issue of a third. Removal and replacement of boiler components is necessary to prevent the leakage of steam and water into the units causing deterioration internally. Of the three boiler units the hospital has, Unit Two must be repaired within several weeks to prevent further damage.Unit One is showing signs of rust and wear that requires major repairs within one year. Failure of either or both units risks hospital closure. Additional work to be completed includes: new diesel pumps, new boiler skins and re-insulating boilers one and two. Unit Three has safety issues that need to be repaired. Once this project is completed, the three boiler units will have an additional 20 year lifespan andprovide the rural residents access to improved healthcare services.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct and make improvements to the Rural Water Districts water distribution system. The districts original system was installed in 1965. Due to the systems age, design and construction practices used at that time, the district experiences leaks, high pressure loss and loss of water every year. The proposed project will include a new booster pump station, construction of a new 400,000 gallon elevated storage tank and installation of new water supply lines. Once the project is completed, the district will have a safe and reliable water system for many years to come.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to focus on three schools located in frontier communities to deliver high-quality distant learning services. The three schools are Holy Family School, St. Joseph Catholic School, and Sacred Heart School, which together serve approximately 300 students. This project provides real-time, interactive telecommunication distance learning equipment, to deliver educational instruction and substance use prevention training to students living in Great Bend, Ellinwood, and Ness City, Kansas. This project will also help connect rural schools to support rural residents throughout Southwest Kansas.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to build a telemedicine and distance learning network between 19 counties in Kansas. This project will improve our core infrastructure by expanding access points to internet / Wi-Fi connectivity and introduce state of the art dual-purpose equipment for distance education programs and behavior health services at our adult correctional facilities located in the rural areas of Winfield, Norton, Stockton, El Dorado, Oswego, Ellsworth, Learned and Lansing, Kansas. Through connections between the hub site and end-user sites, the project will provide 7,600 residents of the correctional facilities with the opportunity to access education programs, teacher resources, and secondary and post-secondary level instruction, while also expanding access to therapeutic services for residents in restrictive housing settings to engage in the full range of necessary treatment and support services to aide in their recovery process.

funding_code: TELEMEDICINE- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to implement telemedicine systems in parts of Kansas, Colorado, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Texas. Morton County Health Systems in Elkhart, Kan., will be the hub site. The system will serve approximately 144,000 residents in Morton, Stevens, Seward, Haskell, Grant, Finney, Kearney, and Stanton counties in Kansas; Baca County in Colorado; Cimarron and Texas counties in Oklahoma; Union County in New Mexico; and Dallam, Hansford, Ochiltree, and Sherman counties in Texas.

funding_code: DLT GRANTS - SUBSTANCE USE DISORDER - MEDICAL
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the Morton County Health System to purchase and install stationary and portable medical examination equipment to serve rural residents in Morton County, Kansas and Cimarron and Texas Counties in Oklahoma. The project will provide state of the art diagnosis and care to patients, in addition to opioid and substance abuse education. The total number of rural residents who will benefit from the project is estimated to be 144,000.

funding_code: TELEMEDICINE- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand Hub/End-User and End-User sites located in counties designated as rural. project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install heating and air conditioning systems and new lighting in the junior and senior high school facilities in Burlingame, Kansas. The current systems were installed in 1960 and are antiquated, inefficient and not environmentally friendly. Installation will include flat panel LED lights, to improve the quality of light as well as use resources more efficiently, and replacement of the entire heating and air conditioning system with a variant refrigerant flow zoning system. Due to the COVID-19 virus, it has come to light that older heating and air conditioning systems do not provide healthy air quality, nor do they help in preventing the spread of disease. Once the project is completed, the schools will provide students, staff and visitors with facilities that will provide a healthier and more conducive learning environment.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing for a water system improvement project. The improvements will include: cleaning and repairing water supply wells, repairing and rehabilitating the chlorine treatment facility, building a water supply transmission line from the well field to the city, building a booster pump station and interconnect to Osage County Rural Water District Number Five, repairing and rehabilitating two elevated water storage tanks, installing a telemetry system, and upgrading the citys aging distribution system infrastructure. This project has already received $600,000 from a Community Development Block Grant; in May 2017 they received $30,000 -- Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant, in April 2020 they received $4,152,000 and $1,409,000 from Water and Environmental Loan and Grant funds. Once this project is complete, the city will have reliable and safe drinking water for many years to come.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used torehabilitate the existing wastewater collection system, via pipe lining, manhole rehabilitation via cementitious liner, replacement of the lift station, and improvements to the gates, valves and weir plates at the lagoon treatment facility. The current facility is not in compliance with their Water Pollution Control Permit and they have set forth a schedule of compliance. The excessive inflow and infiltration is contributing to health, safety, and compliance issues. This wastewater system consists of vitrified clay tile pipe that is 60 years old. The system is installed at a level where much of it is below the groundwater level, which leads to substantial inflow and infiltration through the tile pipe and manholes. This high level of inflow and infiltration overloads the treatment lagoon system, which causes significant discharges of inadequately treated wastewater. This is also of critical concern, because the properties in the City are all on private wells, which are susceptible to contamination due to the shallow groundwater issue. Kansas Department of Health and Environment has cited the City for the failures of their system, and they must take corrective actions to avoid further enforcement actions. The City received a Rural Development Predevelopment Planning Grant of $22,000 in 2020. Along with these funds the City contributed $8,000 to cover the predevelopment costs associated with this project. Once this project is completed, the City will have a safe and reliable wastewater system, which will be in compliance with their permit and protects the private wells from future contamination.

The excessive inflow and infiltration is contributing to health, safety, and compliance issues. This wastewater system consists of vitrified clay tile pipe that is 60 years old. The system is installed at a level where much of it is below the groundwater level, which leads to substantial inflow and infiltration through the tile pipe and manholes. This high level of inflow and infiltration overloads the treatment lagoon system, which causes significant discharges of inadequately treated wastewater. This is also of critical concern, because the properties in the City are all on private wells, which are susceptible to contamination due to the shallow groundwater issue. Kansas Department of Health and Environment has cited the City for the failures of their system, and they must take corrective actions to avoid further enforcement actions. The City received a Rural Development Predevelopment Planning Grant of $22,000 in 2020. Along with these funds the City contributed $8,000 to cover the predevelopment costs associated with this project. Once this project is completed, the City will have a safe and reliable wastewater system, which will be in compliance with their permit and protects the private wells from future contamination.

project_name: Elevated Water Storage Replacement and Clearwell Relocation
funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 150,000-gallon elevated storage tank and two, 20,000-gallon above-ground storage tanks. The project will relocate the high service pump station, which allows the city to abandon 2,200 feet of old transmission line. The project will install approximately 650 feet of 8-inch waterline, a new telemetry system, and generators at the wells and high service pump stations for emergency power. This project will replace a 1918 stand pipe and cast-iron transmission line to the city to an underground clear well that is in poor condition and leaking. It will also replace waterlines that are cast iron, service lines that are copper, lead and steel and water meters. Most of the citys mains are assumed to be over 100 years old and need to be replaced. The city currently does not have a backup power supply for their water service. Once the project is completed, the city will have a safe and reliable system to deliver water to residents of their community.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used toreplace portions of the existing gas supply line that runs along Kansas Highway 99 between the City of Wamego and Interstate 70. There will be construction of approximately 28,000 feet of new high pressure natural gas main along with tracer wire, 2 service connections, driveway restoration, gas main test stations and purging and abandonment of the existing natural gas main. The citys current gas system has been in place since 1960. Their current distribution system is in good working order and being properly maintained. There are several segments of the current system that are in good shape and no repairs or replacements will be made at this time. But there have been multiple leaks found in the gas feeder lines. These leaks have occurred due to corrosion. The corrosion is severe enough that it has occurred throughout the entire steel gas feeder line and is getting worse and will continue to get worse if nothing is done. To complete this project the City has acquired grant funds from the Kansas Department of Commerce in the form of a Community Development Block Grant in the amount of $600,000.00 along with a Rural Development Community Facility Disaster Grant in the amount of $303,300.00. When the project is completed the City will have a safe and reliable means of getting natural gas to rural residents of their community and the surrounding area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will construct and improve the citys water distribution system. The project will provide the city with a 200,000 gallon elevated water storage tank, upgrade the existing Little Bear elevated storage tank, and install approximately 12,000 linear feet of 12 inch water line and approximately 2.700 linear feet of eight inch water line. Repairs to the Fall River dam will also be made. The project will include other infrastructure improvements like a new lift station and sewer repairsfor the hospital and a new river intake structure (originally part of the project, was previously funded by a $1,000,000.00 Emergency Community Water Assistance Grant on July 12, 2018). These funds will allow the needed improvements be completed, keep user rates at a reasonable cost to customers, and bring the system up to compliance with State standards. The City will then have a safe and reliable system to supply water to residents for many years to come.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make improvements to the water distribution system of the City of Fulton. Improvements will include replacing the original water distribution system, meter assemblies, valves and fire hydrants. The city received a $15,000 grant in August 2019, from Rural Development via the Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant to complete a Preliminary Engineering Report. Once completed, the city will be able to provide continued water service to the community for years to come.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: AMERICAN INDIAN AND ALASKA NATIVE TRIBAL GOVERNMENTS
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide a historic rehabilitation to the Hosford and Gagnon Block Building, originally constructed in 1887. This project will be used to fund the exterior enclosure construction efforts for the rehabilitation project, in addition to necessary core and shell improvements for accessibility and life safety under applicable adopted building codes. Significant renovation of the interior fit up areas will occur in following phases. The renovated building will bring several key economic improvements to the nearby community of Rulo, Nebraska with new programming and proposed usage of the structure. The ground level bays will offer both a trading post mercantile usage, and a gallery setting that relates to the sites historic nature. The upper floor renovation is planned to support a flexible use, with a large center space for future business training and business incubator opportunities. This project is expected to assist a minimum of four small and emerging businesses and create at least four full-time equivalent jobs in the next three years.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct levee improvements for flood protection for the communities of Elwood, Wathena and rural areas of Doniphan County. Funds will be used for the design of the project that includes the preparation of reports, plans and specifications needed to make improvements to the levee. The construction will address the following issues: raising the levee, installing relief wells, making drainage structure improvements, replacing conduits and pipes going into and along Peters Creek at several stations along the way, and replacing the drainage structure. Once the project is completed, it will provide the residents and rural area improved flood protection and increased safety.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding to complete improvements on the City of Highlands water system.. The project is to construct a new ion exchange treatment plant and a non-discharging lagoon. In Sept., 2021, Rural Development obligated a $1,262,000.00 loan and $534,000.00 in grant funding for this project. Other funding anticipated includes a Kansas Department Of Commerce Community Development Block Grant of $600,000.00 and Kansas Department of Health and Environment debt forgiveness of $600,000.00. The project will correct compliance issues with the current water system and the community will have safe and reliable water for years to come.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help the City of Coolidge construct a new two-cell non treatment system followed by a non-discharging wetlands cell. This project will ensure the city will have a safe and sanitary treatment system for years to come.

naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment and provide funds for Hodgeman County Health Center. The Center experienced a loss of revenue in 2020 from the COVID-19 pandemic. The funds will purchase a colonoscope and scope cleaner and replace lost revenue. funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER PUBLIC BUILDING & IMPROVEMENT RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a shipping container to convert into public restrooms for a city park in Jetmore. The current restroom is in poor repair and is not accessible for individuals with disabilities. The new container will be placed on concrete footings and engineered to include two bathrooms each including a flush toilet, a sink and will be accessible for individuals with disabilities. The outside will be beautified, making it more appealing and consistent with the surrounding environment. Once the project is completed, this facility will provide safe and reliable services in the park.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to recover lost revenues, improve electronic health records and provide additional information via computer platform for Sumner County Home Health Agency in Wellington. This agency is Medicare-certified to provide intermittent skilled nursing, therapy services and personal care to patients in their homes. The COVID-19 pandemic prevented the agency from providing home services for a three month period in 2020. This resulted in the loss of $122,218.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help purchase and install eight storm sirens for the city of Wellington. The sirens will replace six storm sirens within the city limits, and sirens at Wellington Lake and Wellington Airport, that have recently experience mechanical issues. All of these sirens can be activated by Sumner County 911, Wellington Law Enforcement and Wellington Fire/Emergency Medical Services. Once the new sirens are installed, residents and visitors in the area will have a more reliable emergency warning system.

project_name: Elevated Water Storage Replacement and Clearwell Relocation
funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help complete improvements to the water supply system for the City of Caldwell. These improvements include the replacement of the standpipe with a 150,000 gallon elevated storage tank, replacement of the clear-well with two 20,000 gallon storage tanks, replacement of a pump station, install approximately 650 feet of waterline, and modernize controls at the wells. Funds already assigned to this project include a prior award from Rural Developments Water and Waste Disposal Loan in the amount of $1,558,000.00 (awarded on March 31, 2021) and Kansas Department of Commerce-Community Development Block Grant in the amount of $600,000.00. This project ensures that the city will have safe and reliable water for many years to come.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help Meadowlark Farm, LLC, purchase and install a 14.8-kilowatt rooftop solar photovoltaic renewable energy system. Meadowlark Farm, founded in 2010, is a pick-your-own orchard near Rose Hill that produces peaches, apples, strawberries and hard cider. The project is expected to replace 21,982 kilowatt hours (kWh) of electricity per year, which is 62 percent of the companys electricity use, and enough to power 2.2 homes. The project is expected to save the company $2,093 per year in electrical costs.

funding_code: REAP IRA EEI GRANT UNRESTRICTED (FY 22/23)
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
naics_description: FATS AND OILS REFINING AND BLENDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install energy efficient improvements for North Star Feeds of Atchison. North Star Feeds will replace their existing boiler with a more efficient model, insulate and shorten their water and steam lines, install a return to conserve energy and water, replace existing tanks with new insulated storage tanks, and replace existing truck-mounted diesel pumps with efficient electric models. The project is expected to save 850 kilowatt-hours (kWh) of electricity, 8,692,000 cubic feet of natural gas, 17,755 gallons of diesel fuel, and 3,410 gallons of unleaded gasoline per year, which is a 73 percent reduction in energy use and enough electricity to power more than 300 homes. The project is expected to save the company $154,886 per year in energy costs.
